i'm new to town and from texas. i was hoping to get some good tex mex. i ordered the fajita combo plate, the easiest and tastiest dish to make. sadly it was dry and bland. presentation was very poor. it looked like a chicken and beef stir fry with tough dry meat and veggies. normally the meats and veggies should be separated on the plate and grilled on their own area, not stir fried. i told the waiter this issue, he brought me back a new plate and didn't apologize. the meat was still dry, salty now and still bland and stir fried. 

based off other reviews, people got food poisoning from the fajita plate. i wouldn't be surprised if there was a cross contaimation problem in the kitchen cooler.

text:
i love einstein bagels and have frequented 
various locations around vegas for over 20 years. sadly, today will be our last visit to this location. after several incorrect orders (everything from wrong cream cheese to two bottoms on my bagel to missing items), i finally decided to email the company a few months ago. the managers reached out to me and tried to make it right. since then, unfortunately, things have only slightly improved. i visit every single sunday and my order is almost always the same and yet they always toast the wrong bagels, forget ingredients on my sandwich and/or forget my side (potato salad) and pickle or leave out an entire bagel. today, i once again had to ask for my potato salad, didn't even bother to ask for my pickle because it makes me feel like a nag. as the employee handed me the potato salad, she said "and your extra  jalapenos are on the jalapeno bagels" (something i always order but don't always get); i considered letting her know that unfortunately they had toasted them which i didnt want and failed to toast my everything bagel which i did ask for (and all of that was noted on the screen above the food making area-i checked) but she had already turned to walk away. in my car, i ate my sad veg out sandwich, which was not toasted like i ordered and missing the cucumbers and the arugula (it only contained one unripe yellow tomato which i removed, two red onions and some spinach and the cream cheese/hummus). i told my son sorry about the toasted jalapeno bagels but that i just couldn't complain again...i hate having to complain. some of the employees look at me with no smile when i enter and i think they think i'm an annoying customer just because i want my order made correctly. the lady manager has been kind and always reminds the employees to make sure my order is right...but it usually still isn't. idk, i'm starting to think maybe it's on purpose at this point :( so we will have to find another sunday morning breakfast place.

text: had a reservation for 7 got there a little before, was told they were cleaning tables and it would be a 10-20 minute wait. kind of defeats purpose of reservation but it was only 8 minute wait so not a big deal. atmosphere nice and rustic but tables are a little close together so if you are overweight or pregnant i do not think you would sit comfortably here. food is fancy and on the higher price scale, not incredibly expensive though, like a plain burger is 12.95 with fries or a plain caesar salad no meat 9.95 (examples just for price scale). i dislike that the meals come with predetermined sides and you do not have a choice. there were multiple items i would have tried had it not been for the sides because of allergy. i ended up ordering chicken piccata but when i received it there were bell peppers which i am allergic to so i sent it back and asked for it without the rice ended up getting just a plain breaded chicken when it came back out. server was very nice though and comped it. the breading of the chicken had a very slight amount of star anise in it and it gave it a very nice subtle flavor jolt (for those of you who do not know star anise tastes like mild black licorice which i know sounds gross but it does add a good flavor). my partner got a steak which had a potato wedges and a broccoli side. the broccoli did not look too appetizing and he did not eat it but the wedges looked amazing (though they were very large cut). the bathroom was pretty dirty (seriously people need to clean up after yourselves in public) and the toilets looked so small to me. although i was upset about the lack of adhering to a reservation which is detracting stars, the experience was not bad and service was great. would try again but maybe on a weeknight as it was crowded on a saturday night

wow! delicious! i've regularly passed up this place in lieu of other options, but recently decided to make it a point to try every pizza place in the area and boy was i blown away. 

for beginners, i ordered during some pretty unfortunate weather (snow) and the lady who took my order was very kind and apologized that she couldn't give me an exact time that my pizza would arrive. however, i expected this from any delivery service at the time... again, because of the snow but also because of sunday football. despite her quote that it would arrive within the hour, it only took 40 minutes! 

then second the pizza arrived, i opened the box and took a huge bite because i was starving and in the middle of shoveling snow... it was so delicious, i stopped everything and went inside to keep eating.

the cheese was gooey and a really nice texture. the pepperoni and sausage had great flavor but the star of the show was definitely the cheese and the crust! crispy just around the edges but it had a great chew.

only thing i will advise is that you eat it right away! once it starts to get cold, it loses a lot of the characteristics that i love about it, but that's with most pizzas.

text: this is the top of my list for favorite restaurants. they've preserved the history of this classic place (and one time speakeasy) with beautiful fireplaces in some of the rooms, a solid door with a slit of a window which was common during the prohibition era, the original ovens set permanently in a bricked wall, a gorgeous bar (just note the wood work there and through the other rooms), a wall of windows that overlook the wildlife that come to visit & feed from the river below. the wait staff is beyond excellent and their menu features an almost endless array of appetizers, entrees and desserts. you'll find classics such as prime rib, beef wellington, or lobster tail, scampi and fish; there's also duck and other game, not to mention additional specials for that day. the bar can also accommodate tastes that range from classic to contemporary. i'm telling you,  you will enjoy an experience that is very hard to find nowadays. and if there are just two in your party, ask for table #26. you won't be disappointed.

text:
this middling family-oriented pizza joint was described to me as "low cultural capital food for people with high economic capital." while that's a bit harsh for a charlotte-area pizza place, the sentiment is generally in the right direction. as a native-new jerseyian and current resident of new york, i'm probably a tough customer to please when it comes to pizza south of the mason-dixon line. that being said, it's not an impossible task. mellow mushroom is lovely (as is other pizza around charlotte) and as long as the place doesn't try to be something it's not, pizza is still pizza. that's where brixx gets things wrong. though the beer selection is good and affordable, the pizza focuses on ~wild and crazy~ flavors, but forgets that sauce is not optional and that the crust needs to be doughy and like tire retread. 

all in all, it's a decent, affordable place to spend time with friends and family (or other large groups), but don't expect the pizza to rock you.

edit: the people here are very sweet and i'm maybe too harsh when it comes to pizza.

text:
so, subway comes out with this new "ultimate cheesy garlic bread". it allows you to order your favorite "sub" and have all of the fixings (along with cheese of your choice)...but for an additional charge (roughly $1.59) you get their italian bread with garlic spread and shredded cheese toasted on the bun before your meat/veggies of choice go on the bread.

well. apparently at this location they either have no clue what they are doing (the idiots making sandwiches don't know how to make sandwiches in general) or are just out to rip off customers as much as possible.

they smashed and tore my wife's bread open. they then use as little meat as possible and made four separate areas of folded meat.
when it came to my meatball (regular price $5.95 - with choice of cheese included for free), i wanted the ultimate cheesy garlic bread ($7.59 - additional charge for the garlic spread and melted cheeses on the bread). 
the employee just made a few large blobs of the garlic spread - did not spread it out across the entire bread. he then (without melting the spread and cheese) put the meatballs and (about a gallon) sauce. the rude female employee then asked if i wanted it toasted.  i said it should have been toasted before the meatballs were put on. (if i decided not to toast it, i would have been eating cold cheese and blobs of cold garlic spread!!) she said it can be done either way, this is the way we do it. (there is no way that garlic spread and cheese would have melted properly with the luke-warm meatballs and sauce piled on top) 
so, she toasts the sandwich. then she wraps it up. my wife asked why i didn't get cheese in my sandwich, and the female said "there is cheese on there!". my wife said "no, we wanted provolone cheese". we were told that we could not have provolone cheese since we got the cheesy garlic bread. i asked why i couldn't get cheese, and she said that i would be charged for extra cheese if i insisted on the provolone!!! now by this point, all of the sauce piled on my sandwich was oozing out everywhere and seeping out through the wrapper (she went ahead and wrapped it up, refusing to put any more cheese on the sandwich!!) they continued to argue with us and tell us that we have to pay extra if we want provolone. we tried explaining that the sandwich is already charged $1.59 more for the special bread. they insisted that because if the bread, i am not allowed to have any cheese other than the cheese used to make it "ultimate cheesy". 
she then called either the manager (or owner) and said that we ordered the sandwich,  and when we saw the price,  we wanted our money back. i said "no, i just wanted the provolone (that the meatball is always available to be added for free) on my sandwich". she then told the person on the phone that i want "extra cheese" but am refusing to pay the charge for extra cheese. i said i don't want extra cheese....i want the normally included cheese that the employee refuses to put on my sandwich.

the person on the phone then said just give them the money.  i said i didn't want the money. i just want to eat my sandwich the way i want (this is subway....i can make my sandwich the way i like it, correct?!?)

this is when i was told that i was not allowed to have my sandwich. she gave me my money and said - with a smug and ignorant tone - have a good night.

as we walked out of the store without my food,  the gentleman that made.my sandwich began arguing with me that he knows how to make a sandwich. he made it right.

we have had issues here before, and have witnessed issues leading to police being called.

definitely the last time anyone i know will ever visit this horrible location.

text:
i picked this place to have dinner with some friends; it was quite close to where we were having an event that evening, and my alternate option was a place called "carnivores" which i disqualified exclusively because i didn't want to hear the vegetarian in the group whine about it. 

based on the recommendations of other reviews, i made a reservation for the 4 of us on a friday evening. i'm really glad i did, too, because it got quite crowded! 

the atmosphere was cozy. the tables in my area are close enough that navigating to the bathroom was like navigating a waist-high hedge maze, but not so close that seating was uncomfortable. there's also a bar area with several tvs.

the food was good. i honestly don't remember what i ordered, but i'm pretty sure i ate it all. the menu is larger than i expected for a place so small, and it seems like a good mix of traditionally euro-american fare that is common in this region: burgers, fish, pasta, salads, etc. my friend took his leftover pasta home to his wife, and she told me she enjoyed it, too.

staff was friendly, drinks were prompt, our orders were correct, and other customers were loud (as per any neighborhood bar and grill on a friday evening) but certainly not impolite.

everyone in the group asked me if i'd been there before, because it definitely feels like a little cozy gem of a restaurant known mostly by locals. i can thank online reviews for pointing me here!

my husband made reservations at annabella's restaurant for thanksgiving day and let me tell you it was just fabulous.  i told the chef and manager that i would let leisure world know.  they have been under new management since may 2018.  we had booked our reservation late this year and could not be seated at mccormick ranch or wrigley manson.  annabelle's was available although the old reviews were not so good.  we booked it anyway because it was close and available. i am so happy we did not listen to the bad reviews 

we went and it was better than our past experience at mccormick ranch and not as expensive.  it was buffet style and had all the traditional varieties of food for thanksgiving.  the gravy and stuffing were excellent.  they also had a breakfast brunch buffet and a wonderful salad bar with specialty meats, salad, and cheeses, dessert table.  the buffet price included free champagne or mimosa's upon your arrival.  we would highly recommend annabelle's with it's vintage 1950's glamour and gorgeous chandeliers.  so, if you want atmosphere and fine dining it is here at annabelle.  they are also open for breakfast lunch and dinner daily with outdoor pool view patio seating. we definitely are going there again and again and it's so close.  i hope you take my recommendation and visit this restaurant so they can stay in business.  we need a fine dining place close to l.w. 

sally & dave perry

text:
we love going to the village pubs around town, for its great homemade tasting food, and awesome prices.
this visit was our first time at this location, in summerlin.
to start things off, the hostess took our drink order, and they had no syrup in them. (coke) we let her know, and she had the guy fix the machine.
the (older lady) waitress finally took our order, after walking by us at our table several times.
 we ordered the prime rib specials. she brings us our soup, and we finish it, with still no drinks. the hostess (younger girl) walks by and says, "oh, you guys still haven't gotten your drinks yet", and we say nope. pretty upset by that point. it honestly felt as if because we weren't a regular customer of that location, that we were intentionally being ignored. especially since the older waitress made it a point to chat with every other couple she was helping.
our food finally comes out, after almost an hour, and both of our prime ribs were terribly dry. the green beans were cold, and the potato was almost there as well.
we aren't ones to complain, so we did not say anything. my wife could not eat hers, although i did try to eat mine. trying not to waste it.
a male waiter, and possibly manager came over to clear our plates and asked us how it was. i had to be honest and let him know the meat was very dry, so he said he would comp one. not what we were expecting, but a nice gesture. he asked our waitress if we mentioned it, and she said no. of course, because we didn't want to make it a big deal. he did still comp one, so that was nice of him.
definitely won't be back to this location, but will visit our other favorite locations around town.

text:
this is kind of an oddball fusion cuisine that looks like it shouldn???t work on paper, but it???s really fantastic. the concept stems from the proprietors having lived in the midwest, texas, and alaska (hence the north and south name) and the food is this surprising amalgamation of texas bbq, fresh pacific seafood and wisconsin comfort cooking. i guess the danger in a restaurant that tries to have something for everyone is that they end up doing a mediocre version of everything???not so at north and south. the bbq is as tender, smokey, and flavorful as from any bbq joint in central texas. the seafood is always fresh and flavorfully prepared. and the down-home dishes tie it all perfectly together. 

the beer selection leaves something to be desired, and the drink prices are a bit on the high side. still, the food is the centerpiece of the show and isn???t to be missed. in a city with so much great food,
north and south still manages to stand out. 

be sure to call ahead for a table, the place is pretty small and fills up fast. large groups can be an issue as well. the service is fantastic and the atmosphere is great. it???s a dining highlight in madison that still doesn???t take itself too seriously. enjoy!

text:
unfortunate for us i suppose.  

front of house: staff was fantastic and the seating/interior was very cool. quaint space with perfect lighting made it a very intimate experience. park at heinens for an easy walk. 

drinks: umami 75 and the rye mule were unremarkable.  lemon slice still had seeds and was a bit ripped when sliced. 

small plates: at the suggestion of the waiter we went with the specials, yellowtail hamachi and braised crispy sweetbreads.  the yellowtail was fine in terms of texture though there was no real flavor of the candied lemon and jalapeno.  the sweetbreads were chewy, not crispy, and a bit slopped on the plate.  sauce on the sweetbreads was very good.

main course: again with one of the specials, the big eye tuna had no "spicy ginger" or "braised greens".  was also overcooked as the sear was grey going about a half inch into the center while being blackened on just one side.  the worst offender was the short rib udon.  best described as roast beef squares in the udon.  again with no taste of jalapeno the dish was a decent broth was nice greens and noodles but the meat absolutely was akin to a braised beef that was chopped up and tossed directly into a pot of broth to leech out all it's flavor and become a crock pot roast. 

no dessert as we had spent enough already.  for 140 all in (30 of which was the tip for great service), we unfortunately won't be back.  these are lola prices that fail to deliver on quality.

text:
exceptional underground elegance!
having grown up on the pacific coast, i am very used to fresh seafood and had high expectations from what i had read about the salt cellar.

when i dined here with my family, my high expectations were completely fulfilled. i was amazed at how fresh and good everything we had to eat was. 

my daughter got to pick out her very own lobster (which was the size of my forearm!).  she loved it, both as the food and the experience.

i ordered a plate of crab legs, and this is where things got fun. they bring out the tray, and these legs are huge, but then, the server cracked the crab for me! i've eaten a lot of crustacean, but haven't ever had someone open it for me.
it was fantastic! all the pleasure eating the crab (with butter and lemon of course) without any of the work of digging the meat out of the shell.

while i can't afford to eat here all that often, i'm sure i'll be back to the best seafood i've had in arizona.

thanks to everyone at the salt cellar for a wonderful meal and experience!

text:
if you are not a fan of various kinds of animals being brought into an eatery such as a parrot(i'm not lying or exaggerating), then don't patronize subway. when i reported this as a customer concern,  i received the following replay followed by my follow up response.

mr. mccarthy ???
 
i wanted to apologize for the customer who brought a parrot into our store.  i agree that pets should not be allowed in restaurants however under arizona law we are not allowed to question the validity of a person???s service animal.  if a customer tells us their animal is a service animal, we must allow them to bring it into the store.
 
i apologize that my employee thought it was cool???they were wrong, however it is a very difficult situation that even with training, many quick-service employees are not comfortable handling, as it can turn confrontational very quickly, and result in legal action.
 
i will once again speak with my staff about service animals and the rights and laws protecting both the restaurant as well as the individuals with those needs.  if you can let me know which employee, even a brief description, i will specifically speak to them about it as well.
 
thank you
 
philip cohen

mr. cohen,

the restaurant employee did not bother to question the patron about whether or not the parrot was a service animal and i doubt that a parrot would qualify as such, although in this day and age, nothing would surprise me. so on that basis, i will spread the word that subway allows such animals in their restaurants based on the assumption that they are allowed under arizona law, whatever misconceived kind of law that would be.

personally, i would have told the patron to leave and return without the parrot. it???s as simple as that. he gets served, and other patrons are not bothered or offended.

text:
we (husband and self) love the firepit.  this is the restaurant that we go to instead of any chain when we want to stay within 20 minutes of our home.  the food is always 100% consistent and delicious.  the pics are of out last visit on  02/09/19.   i had the thai sweet heat shrimp - hard wood grilled shrimp, sweet chili thai sauce, grilled pineapple salsa, fresh scallions, and charred vegetable fried rice with a side of wood fired cornbread . . . husband had the 9oz. center-cut aged sirloin, smashed potatoes, and roasted roasted onions.  we always start with the wood-fired pretzels because yeah - wood fired pretzels!!!!!  we have never had a bad meal at the firepit.  i always call if we are going at prime dinner time on a saturday for reservations and had never had to wait.   

the only reason i did not give 5 stars is because on 3 different occasions,  with one particular waitress, service has been slow.  you should not have to wait for a refill where the manager ends up having to come over to ask you if you want another drink when your empty glasses have been sitting at the edge of the table for 10 minutes, and then wait another 7 minutes after that.  the firepit is not that big in size that this should happen - it is an open dining room plan where all of the tables/booths can be seen by the wait staff.   you can have the best food in the world, but poor service will eventually start to have an effect.  

all in all though, never having a bad meal quality-wise  at the firepit, you should really should try them out, as the food does compensate for the occasional less-than-perfect service. we have been here at least 10 times now, and i still have not tried everything i want to try, and i have had something different every time.

text:
in a sea of mexican restaurants, it's really hard for a place to stand out. authenticity is a gamble, and so is good quality. when you do find a good place, the prices might not be as good.

azteca wins in every department. their menu is varied, the food is pretty authentic, the atmosphere is great, and the prices are excellent. the women often wear colorful traditional mexican style dresses. sometimes they even have a mariachi band!

my personal favorite is the mexican stir fry, but classic favorites like enchiladas and tacos work just fine. the guacamole (which they will hand-make at your table) is awesome, if a bit pricey. the cost is welcome for the generous and delicious helping of guacamole you get.

the desserts are awesome too. the flan at this place is to die for, seriously. i can't come here without getting it. 

all in all, azteca is hands down my husband's favorite place and where my whole family likes to go for a casual dinner. would give 6 stars if i could.

text:
i have eaten here before and the burgers are awesome, the buns are fantastic and crew is #1, that eating would of been 5 stars. but on my visit on 2/1/19, it was not good.
first off, the weather was cold and everytime the front door opened i could feel a draft, even with double door entry. plus, we were sitting right in front of the kitchen, which is farthest from front door. they need to install a heater above the front door pushing the cold air down.
next, the clam chowder was not good. light red in color, and no flavor, yes absolutely no flavor. i had about 3 very fresh clams in it, but that was it. i have been to multiple seafood places on east and west coast, and claim chowder is my forte. this clam chowder needs work.

next, i got the drunken mushroom burger. the brioche bun was fantastic and so was the meat, but besides that it was very bland. it was suppose to have wine infused mushrooms, but only tasted it maybe in one or two bites. 

not too busy at 5:30 pm, and we had to hunt our waitress to order our food. she was great initially in taking our drink order and seeing if we wanted to get appetizers, but after that all down hill on getting service.

there was only 2 silverware settings for 5 of us and we asked for more. she came back with only one saying that is all they currently had? she never came back with more,,,good thing 3 of us had burgers. that meant we had no napkins for two people so i grabbed some paper ones on the shelves below where they serve the food to staff. again because we could not find our waitress.

what should of been a 35-45 minute dinner turned out to be an hour due to waiting to find our waitress again to get our bill and doggy bags. made us rush to our meeting at 7:15. 

so, if they correct the wait service, cold air blowing in and the clam chowder,  this place would get 5 stars. as i said, first visit 5 stars, i am generous at 3 with this visit.

text: had the pleasure of visiting the sisters tea room for the first time yesterday.  our daughter-in-law was visiting from michigan and we went for lunch (my wife could not join us because she was working).  we really enjoyed the feeling you get walking into the place.  being a century (plus) old home, it's more a feeling of visiting relatives at their home, rather than going into a restaurant.  nicely decorated rooms and fireplace for the holidays, gave it that extra warm feeling. we were greeted by teresa as we entered, and since we were early, decided to browse around the gift shop, where they sell a large variety of packs of loose leaf tea.  for lunch i had the mandarin orange salad with their homemade dressing, and the tea sandwich plate.  my daughter-in-law had the broccoli cheddar quiche and we shared an order of the scone (1 apricot white chocolate, and 1 sweet cream).  i've tried scones before and don't really eat them very often, but since we were in a tea room, and my daughter-in-law didn't want to eat both of them, we split them. this place really knows how to make a scone. they were warm,  perfect texture, and delicious. the quiche came out steaming hot, and my daughter-in-law enjoyed it very much.  the salad was light, and  so good with the homemade dressing. the egg salad tea sandwich was also very good, as was the cucumber with cream cheese spread tea sandwich (something i had never eaten before).  our waitress, teresa was very friendly and knowledgeable about the many teas, and the entrees.  in fact all the employees we met were very nice, and made you feel at "home".  we both enjoyed our tea ( one pot darjeeling and one pot of earl grey creme), and each picked out several packs of teas to buy for home.  it was a fun, relaxing time and look forward to returning.

text: best bbq i have in the area. we had traditional southern "meat and three" combos, which is a meat and 3 sides. the brisket was delicious and so was the pulled pork. mind you my girlfriend is from texas and i lived in memphis for a time, so know what good bbq is supposed to be like. the meat was smokey, moist and simply seasoned. the brisket had a nice smoke ring. sauce is available on the side and was a choice of sweet traditional sauce, and the far rarer mustard based sauce found in parts of the carolinas. the sides were equally delicious, including a fantastic mac & cheese, mashed sweet potato seasoned with a bit of chipolte, red beans & rice, and a great slab of corn bread which was moist and not overly sweet. note: call your order in for pickup later. they stay open until they run out, but if you call in they will hold the meat aside, and since they have to prep the meat for the next day, you can pick up the order at the time you set up.

text:
went to dinner with my mom here for my first time.  it was rather empty and ordered a italian stallion on white (choices between white or wheat) with seasoned french fries.  the bread that they served before our meals came out was pretty good.  however, when the meal came out is when i had some issues. 

the sandwich i was served was on wheat instead of white, and the fries were a only little above room temperature. i took two bites and had realized it was wheat.  at first my mom and i thought that it had been just because it had been baked or something like that.  when i asked the server if they had gotten my order right she took it back and talked to the cook i assume.  she came back and told me that they were out of white bread for sandwiches. 

i many issues with this.  firstly, why was i not informed of this before ordering the sandwich or even upon receiving it? secondly, how does a restaurant run out of one of the most popular types of sandwich breads? especially on a lazy not-busy monday like when i was there. if you have a staple item on the menu (like a lot of different sandwiches) you should not skimp on how many base ingredients you buy such as bread. i estimate you should have at least 1/8 extra of your average that you sell that weekday. last are the hypothetical implications of something like this.  if the servers don't inform you of the shortage of items while ordering and after serving it to you.  what were to happen if it was a customer that was allergic to the one choice and not the other? would they just serve the item they were allergic to and not say a word like what happened with the white/wheat switch?  i know the issue i had isn't as severe as that as i had no medical issues because of it. however, you need to ask these questions when you see something like this happen.  it could have been a one time mistake, but are you willing to let it be a one time mistake with someones allergies? 

i also have a sneaking suspicion that they could have said it just because they didn't want to remake the sandwich. it was around 6:15 and it was a monday night with the people winding down for the day. this might just be my cynicism talking but it looked like a guy a couple booths over had a sandwich on white.  however, i'm not going to say that this happened 100% since i have no proof or confirmation from the other guy.  it's only my suspicion and should be treated as a suspicion and not fact. 

in the end, when she brought it back for me the fries were cold and the sandwich was still a bit warm from the hot it was.  overall, the sausage was good in the sandwich, but the situation soured my experience to the point i wasn't really able to enjoy it at all.  the fries were undercooked for my taste and were sagging in addition to being cold.  though them being cold could have been my error since i wasted time in trying to get the order right. next time i'll just let my mom go by herself if she wants to try this place.  she seems to enjoy it and would probably give it a better review herself.

edit: forgot to add that they gave us a 10% off our meal for the switch up.  it just doesn't seem like enough to talk about to be honest since i didn't even get the order i wanted in the first place and got stuck with what they messed up.  similar places would have at least either a)given a cheap dessert for free b) comped the meal that was messed up or c) remade it for free to what you actually wanted.  i would have given this place at least a 2-3 star review had they done more than just a small 15% discount (which came out to a little over 4 bucks discount on an already over $30 for just a slice of pizza, the sandwich, and a bowl of soup.)

text:
when i walked into richardson's, i felt like i was striding into a secret hideaway. their indoor/outdoor patio is gorgeous! plants hang from pergolas and line adobe-like support columns, tables and booths with cushy pillows offer comfortable places to eat, and the heat lamps keep things toasty, is you're not already toasted from the cocktails at the patio bar. 5 stars for ambiance!
the servers were very nice, but maybe a bit slow, although it was a packed house on a saturday night, so some of that is to be expected. 
for appetizers, i had octopus and calamari-delicious. for course 1, a wedge salad with cheese, cabbage, tomatoes, and onions-decent. for course 2, i had a green chili burger with added onions and mushrooms. the beef was cooked well and they were generous with the veggies. the batter on the onion rings was light and tasty. they did forget my tomatoes and didn't omit the bun, as requested, but again, they were slammed. the flop was the cheesecake. it was too tart and pudding-like, not fluffy.
overall, a great place-i'll be back!

text:
we were out-of-town rvers camping at mcdowell mountain park. we googled pizza near me and selected papa murphy's from the reviews. because we were not towing a car, we had to break camp and drive our motor home into town. when we got to their location, my wife went inside to get a menu. they didn't have one, so she took pictures of their menu display. she then asked for their telephone number, so we could call them from our rv when we decided. they didn't know the number. after some time in the back room, they came back with a business card.

i called our order in from the rv. since it took over twenty minutes to get back to camp, we decided to eat our pizza in the rv, and then go back to camp. when i went in to get our dinner, i presented with an uncooked pizza. i was confused. every pizza place i had ever been to during my 60-some years served cooked pizzas. i was told if i didn't want it that was ok and i could go to pizza hut down the street. (hind site, i wish i had done that.) it looked so good that i decided to take it.

we cooked the pizza on our grill following their directions to the "t". five minutes before it was supposed to be done, i lifted the pizza up to see if the crust was getting brown. the crust was beyond the brown color and had advanced to black. the cardboard tray, that was to remain under the pizza during the grilling, was on fire. i turned off the propane and quickly slid the charred pizza on to a cutting board.

the crust was inedible, so i scraped my topping off the crust and rolled it up into a tortilla. it was really pretty good. our dogs love pizza crust, but they walked away from tonight's charcoal bits. the one star i gave is from me. my dogs gave it zero stars.

text:
read my original review below, look at how johnson city fox pizza handles their problems.
mara piccone-we used to order fox pizza from university parkway, johnson city tn weekly or twice a wk. they used to do great job. long ago, if they made mistakes, we call them, they would apologize & fix the problem. that has won our hearts & we kept ordering weekly, generous w/ tips. that changed 2 months ago. i drove on way home, i called.  i'm hearing impaired, asked girl on phone speak clearly, i couldn't understand. her tone became unbelievably rude, she then sarcasticlly spoke loudly. in shock, i didn't say anything & hung up on her. very first time, we didn't order entire month.  finally last month, i moved on, tried order once again. i requested extra tomato sauce on all of'em. pizza delivery arrived; all 3 boxes of pizza was a mess, tossed to side like it was dropped sideways while hot. upset but i decided to let it go. then as we ate 'em we noticed it's not extra sauce, in matter of fact, they all was very very very thinly sauce, almost as if they are out of sauce & they put on what they had left. frustrated, my husband called for me & he filled them in on everything mentioned. then manager lied, he said: i made pizza myself, that was extra sauce. he did not apologize for rude girl or for messing up our pizza. we are looking right at barely any sauce pizza while this manager lied. very insulting.  my 6yrs old daughter cried, she miss fox pizza & she wants to order pizza again. she asked me if it matters if anyone was hateful or if they gets our order wrong, why never come back again. my heart breaks for my little girl but i have to set example to stand our ground because it does matter!  ignorance to disability is not okay, bad customer service is not okay. what i want to know is this, now you seen this review, what are you going to do about it? you just lost $40-$80 weekly from us because of your rude and arrogant employees. are you okay with this kind of behavior and terrible customer relationship at your business?

text:
it is very rare that i write a negative review. unfortunately this one has to be.  we took my mom out to lunch during her one hour lunch break.  we thought we would have plenty of time since it was right around the corner from her job.  by the time the food came, mom only got a couple bites of her burger and fries before she had to leave.  now, the waitress did warn us that the size of the burgers meant that they took longer to cook.  

i am on the ketogenic diet, so i avoid fries, buns, sugar, etc.  i'm used to this challenge, but they wouldn't exchange the side of fries that came with the burger with anything except coleslaw.  i asked to switch it with the side salad ($2.99) for a reasonable upcharge, but no.  so despite the fact that i got a burger without their fancy bun, and asked them not to bring fries, i still had to pay full price for the burger meal and full price for the salad.  very frustrating.  

my mom's regular burger was good but boring.  my niece's ragin' cajun burger was yummy.  my house salad was very disappointing.  just iceberg lettuce with tiny pieces of green pepper, onion, and tomato.  (no cucumbers, even though they were in the menu's description.)  i got the burger with mozzarella and grilled onions and peppers.  it was good, even without the bun.  

the atmosphere is really weird.  it's patchworked together in what seems like a former store or office. they hide the kitchen with curtains and wood lattice.  

i really root for local small businesses, but you have to do a really excellent job at what you do to stand above the big businesses.  i'm afraid that this place just doesn't make the cut.  i'm disappointed.

the service was great.

text:
this restaurant has almost every element of a great restaurant under one roof.

the menu is not cluttered with a ton of different dishes to confuse the guests. it has just the right amount of options with simple descriptions of the dishes. then comes the good prices that completly justify the great taste, quality, and the portion of the food. the  decor is simple but appealing, and everything is clean from the floors to the restrooms.

the restaurant is family-owned, and the owner(s) genuinely care about the customers and do their best for the best customer experience. the owner is hilarious, and very friendly. 

now the best part. the food. i took my first bite on the gyro and couldn't believe how delicious it was! the rice, the bread,  the gyro,  the greek salad??? everything tasted fresh and unbelievably delicious. i was in phoenix for work after a six-hour drive from la in horrible weather and was struggling to find a hotel, but the food here literally made my day. seriously, businesses like this deserve a lot more support.

text:
i cannot say enough good things about ranias catering. for this review, the few things i would like to highlight are 1) the food 2)the level of detail to which rania plans and 3)the amazing staff.

the food at our wedding was unbelievable. rania cooks on site to ensure the food is fresh and hot when it is served to your guests. when choosing your food, rania provides a long list of appetizers, salads and entrees. i absolutely loved the unique options she provided. it was a little intimidating to choose before tasting just because everything sounded so good (because there are so many options, you select initial meal choices before your tasting then can refine your choices after the tasting if needed). our guests have not stopped raving about our food since the wedding, especially the unique appetizers (lamb skewers, grilled dates, thai chicken curry tartlets, and crab cakes to name a few). also, her baker is out of this world. our cakes were delicious and i really liked how i could customize the flavor of each layer of the cake. he also decorated the cake beautifully with fresh flowers.

i do not know what i would have done without rania help and expertise in coordinating everything for the event. we had to rent everything for our venue and also had to bring in the liquor and bars. rania coordinates all of this. at our first meeting, she was able to tell us exactly what we would need in terms of rentals down to the bread bowl. she provided invaluable guidance on timeline, djs, and other vendors. she also provided day-of coordination between all vendors to ensure that everyone was aware of the timeline and on time. i honestly didn???t have to worry about a thing and everything ran so smoothly. it was truly a perfect day and that was in large part due to rania.

lastly i would like to talk about ranias staff. the coordinators, waiters and bartenders were so polite, professional, and attentive to us and our guests. they could not have been any more helpful and made sure everyone had a great time.

it was truly a pleasure to deal with rania. she is an extremely impressive business woman and i have the utmost respect for her and her business. i???m sure you could get good food from another caterer, but rania provides a whole experience that i???m sure is unrivaled. i don???t know what we would have done without her. i can???t wait to have another large event so i can use ranias catering again.

tempted to not even give one star! ever since this rocky's opened there have been numerous issues with our order ... late delivery, missing product, undercooked, overcooked... you get the picture. but we love rocky's and keep hoping for a decent outcome. as a long time retail manager i hate complaining and really like to give people a chance.
but after our last order ... never again! it was 2.5 hours late! the driver showed up once and left because he forget part of the order. after he showed up the first time i called spoke to a woman and she explained what happened and told me she would compensate us. after the order was finally delivered i  checked my bank account and found that i had been charged the entire amount! i called back and spoke to the "manager". i explained the situation and asked how he would handle the promised compensation. he proceeded to lash out and say there was absolutely nothing he could do! i was irritated beyond belief. when we received the entire order one pizza was underdone and the other was completely torched. 
i called once again the next morning and left my name and number for the owner to call. i didn't receive a call until 2 days later ... and remarkably the gentleman sounded very much like the previous "manager " i had spoken too. he told me that he would have the manager on duty that evening reimburse me and that she would call that afternoon when her shift started. never got a call.
i can understand that it's very difficult to get quality people nowadays. however, if the owner of this particular establishment would like any further business from me i suggest a little more involvement on his or her part to upgrade the operation. 
i've spoken to several friends in the area and your local customer base is dwindling.

overall the food tasted good, but towards the end of my meal, an employee came out to wash the floor and was wearing enough cologne to make the remainder of my meal unappetizing. i threw the remainder out and fled the establishment as if someone lit up several stink bombs. 

if you use this place for take out, you should be relatively safe, but i can't recommend it. even without the axe enthusiast, i wouldn't go back. there are better japanese places to go to.

text:
i recall dining at giovanni's years ago when the atmosphere was quieter  and attention was given to every detail - waiters with white towels draped over their arm waiting for your every need.

this year two of my long-time friends decided to revisit the restaurant for our annual christmas dinner.

it's all about the details, but the food has to be worthy also. the waiter was attentive and pleasant. my friend's drink was returned before consuming as she found a lipstick mark on the glass. the drink the second time around was not prepared as requested, missing a critical addition. my friends appetizers of lobster bisque and the prosciutto/grapefruit salad met their approval. the oysters rockefeller appetizer i had was average...i could do a better job myself. my salmon entree was awful - overcooked, fishy, farmed salmon was accompanied by greasy, under cooked potatoes. the dish was returned.

i would not recommend giovanni's. at the price point across the menu, you should expect excellent food, service and clean dinnerware every time.
